## Social Media Variant (1080x1080)

For Instagram, LinkedIn, and other square-format platforms:

```svg
<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 1080 1080" role="img">
  <title>[Metric]</title>
  <desc>[Description]</desc>

  <style>
    /* Same variables as above, adjusted sizes */
    .big-number { font-size: 160px; font-weight: 800; fill: var(--accent); }
    .metric-label { font-size: 36px; font-weight: 600; fill: var(--text); }
    .context { font-size: 24px; fill: var(--muted); }
  </style>

  <rect width="1080" height="1080" fill="var(--bg)" />

  <!-- Centered content with more vertical space -->
  <text x="540" y="430" class="big-number" text-anchor="middle">[Number]</text>
  <text x="540" y="500" class="metric-label" text-anchor="middle">[Label]</text>
  <text x="540" y="550" class="context" text-anchor="middle">[Context]</text>

  <!-- Brand logo -->
  <g transform="translate(980, 1000)" opacity="0.5">
    <!-- logo-mark -->
  </g>
</svg>
```

---

## Guidance

- The number must be the most visually dominant element. If it does not immediately grab attention, make it larger.
- Use one stat per card. Multiple stats dilute impact. For 3-4 stats, use the metric grid pattern from the data-viz template.
- Round numbers for impact: "~$2.4M" reads better than "$2,387,421.33".
- Include context that makes the number meaningful: "up from 32% last quarter" or "2x industry average."
- Choose the viewBox based on output context: 600x400 for blog embeds, 1080x1080 for social, 400x300 for dashboard cards.
- For dark backgrounds, invert: set `--bg` to a dark color and `--text` to white.
